observations.recommendation:
3.11. We recommended that Management, thru the Sanggunian and the Local Finance Committee:

a. implement a more accurate budgeting and forecasting techniques, considering relevant economic factors and historical data to ensure that target revenues and receipts are attainable and for management to exert effort for its accomplishment;

b. observe section 322 of the Local Government Code relative to the declaration of savings as sources of funds for supplemental budget;

c. ensure that savings derived from the 20% Development Fund shall only be re-appropriated to other development project;

d. observe Section 4 and 5, Chapter V of the Budget Operations Manual with respect to Budget adjustment due to changes in target vis-à-vis accomplishments;

3.12. We also recommended that the Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant reconcile financial data contained in the Statement of Appropriations, Obligations and Balances (SAOB) and the Statement of Comparison of Budget and Actual Amounts (SCABAA); and

3.13. We likewise recommended that the Municipal Accountant include the analysis/composition of Government Equity Account in the Notes to Financial Statements in order to reflect the amount actually available for appropriation;

We recommended that:

the Municipal Accountant carefully check that payments for fuel are duly supported with completely filled up driver’s trip tickets as basis in determining the reasonableness of fuel consumption;

the LCE require the concerned employees/officials to prepare the monthly report of official travels and the monthly report of fuel consumption; 

the LCE require the use of Requisition and Issue Voucher (RIV) for all issuances of fuel from the municipal storage tank; and

maintain Subsidiary Ledger of Fuel, Oil & Lubricants for audit verification.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

ensure that all acquisitions and/or construction of infrastructure projects are recognized as assets of the municipality, in accordance with PPSAS and in line with  Section 111 of PD 1445, unless otherwise, indicated in the budget as Subsidy to other LGUs;
effect the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the balances of accounts in the financial statement.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

a) effect the proposed adjusting journal entries (Annexes F & H) to correct the balances of accounts in the financial statements;



b) ensure accurate recording of transactions in the vouchers and journals including its recapitulation entries, posting of accounts in the General Ledgers and forwarding of balances to the financial statements;

c) conduct regular reconciliation of reciprocal accounts, effect simultaneous recording of funds affected, trace and locate relevant documents to serve as basis in analysing the unidentified reconciling items and prepare necessary adjustments;

d) determine the appropriate account for the amount of ₱1,080.43 noted difference under the Trust Fund and the different classification of the amount of ₱59,535.00 and make the necessary adjustments;

e) determine project related to the PPE items amounting to ₱162,233.00 if already completed and effect the necessary transfer to the General Fund. Also, determine the acquisition date and provide the depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation;

f) support the Quarterly Trial Balance with a schedule of subsidiary ledger balances of the controlling accounts;


g) draw journal entries to record all adjustments directly reflected in the Trial Balance and record the same in the General Journal;


h) prepare the Trial Balance showing only the net credit or debit balance and present the accounts in an ascending order to facilitate financial statements preparation and ensure that the amounts shown in the Trial Balance are the same with those presented in the financial statements; and 

i) record closing entries in the General Journal and prepare the corresponding Post-closing Trial Balance.

Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

a) determine the amount of sale of bid documents included in the Due to NGAs account including collections for prior years, if any, and reclassify it as Trust Liabilities. Excess collections after payment of honoraria for completed projects, however, should be reverted back to General Fund as savings pursuant to DBM Circular No. 2004-5A. For succeeding collections, record the same as Trust Liabilities under the General Fund;

b) Ensure accurate and consistent recording of collections and deposits and follow the pro-forma accounting entries in the recording of share in real property tax and fund transfers from other agencies.

c) We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer segregate official receipt booklets for Trust Fund as well as collections then prepare separate report of collection and deposit as attachment of the JEV in the Trust Fund. For the share of SEF in the real property tax collections, deposits are to be made in the GF and a debit advice to be prepared for the transfer on a monthly basis to avoid confusion.

d) We also recommended that management demand liquidation of the Petty Cash Fund amounting to ₱37,774.43 from the petty cash fund custodian.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

a.	ensure that all acquisitions and/or construction of infrastructure projects are recognized as assets of the municipality, in accordance with PPSAS and in line with  Section 111 of PD 1445, unless otherwise, indicated in the budget as Subsidy to other LGUs;

b.	effect the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the balances of accounts in the financial statement.

We recommended that:
a. the Municipal Accountant ensure that the required supporting documents of all claims are complete before affixing her signature in Box A of the disbursement voucher;
b. management ensure that the proper flow of transactions are strictly followed so that only valid and proper claims are approved for payment.

